\section{Performance}{

The portal hosts ~3600 advisory records. Each detail page is fetched once
and saved to a sidecar JSON on disk (see \code{\link[=index_cache]{index_cache()}}); on later runs a
record with an existing sidecar is read straight from disk instead of being
re-fetched, so repeat runs are fast. On a first, cold run, enumerating the
full register can take many minutes and downloading every attachment can use
significant disk space. Always start with a \code{limit} (and ideally a \code{query})
when exploring.

To avoid stressing the server (commissiemer.nl returns HTTP 429 under a
sustained burst), NL requests are throttled to one per second by default
— i.e. a ~1 s delay between detail-page fetches. The rate is configurable
via \code{getOption("planscanR.nl_throttle_rate")} (requests/sec); set it to a
falsy value to disable. The throttle is scoped to NL only.
}

\section{Attachments}{
 per-page split:
Each advice detail page on commissiemer.nl groups PDFs into two on-page
sections, which this handler exposes as separate list-columns:
\itemize{
\item \code{attachment_urls_source} / \code{local_path_source} — files in the
\strong{"Documenten waarop het advies is gebaseerd"} section. These are the
underlying EIA/SEA reports submitted by the proponent and reviewed by the
Commissie. \strong{These are the substantive documents for downstream analysis}
(e.g. for the future \code{classify_assessments()} LLM pipeline).
\item \code{attachment_urls_advice} / \code{local_path_advice} — files in the
\strong{"Adviezen en persberichten"} section: the Commissie's own advisory
reports and press releases.
\item \code{attachment_urls} / \code{local_path} — the union of both (deduplicated),
ordered with source documents first. Required by the planscanR schema.
}

When \code{download = TRUE}, all files in both sections are fetched.
}

